<subSubSection pageId="78" pageNumber="79" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="78.[151,1436,151,391]" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,295,320]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zelazny &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2011" box="[329,528,296,320]" class="Insecta" family="Derbidae" genus="Rhotana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="truncata">
<emphasis box="[329,528,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">Rhotana truncata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles closely 
<taxonomicName authority="Zelazny &amp; Webb, 2011" authorityName="Zelazny &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2011" box="[744,897,296,320]" class="Insecta" family="Derbidae" genus="Rhotana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirashimai" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[744,897,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">R. hirashimai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[906,996,296,319]" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, also from Borneo. It can be separated from that species by the forewings bearing a clearly defined, although faint mark distad of the clavus tip and by the male aedeagus lacking a pointed terminal process.
</paragraph>
